 The new code just merrily calls it and let it<br />&gt; scribble away.  This is as clear-cut a regression as I've ever seen.<br /><br />Yes, I think we'll need to revert it, or do something else drastic<br />like make that initial fp state allocation *much* bigger and then have<br />a "disable xsaves if if it's still not big enough".<br /><br />setup_xstate_features() should be able to easily just say "this was<br />the maximum offset+size we saw", and we can take that to either do a<br />proper allocation, or verify that the static allocation is indeed big<br />enough.<br /><br />Apparently a straight revert doesn't work, if only because things in<br />that area have been renamed very aggressively (both files and<br />functions and variables). Ingo?<br /><br />            Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
